alert.note: Alert for Lewis; Pierce (Washington) Issued by the National Weather Service

info.headline: Flood Warning issued December 05 at 9:43AM PST until December 07 at 2:37AM PST by NWS Seattle
info.description: ...Forecast flooding changed to Minor severity and increased in duration for the following rivers in Washington... Bogachiel River Near La Push affecting Clallam County. ...The Flood Warning is extended for the following rivers in Washington... Nisqually River Near National affecting Lewis and Pierce Counties. Chehalis River Above Doty affecting Lewis County. .Heavy rain will continue in the Washington Cascades through this afternoon. Another 1 to 3 inches of rain is forecast before the rain rates ease. For the Olympic Peninsula Region...including La Push, McDonald Bridge, Sequim, Potlatch, Satsop, Montesano...Moderate flooding is forecast. For the South West Region...including Mud Mtn. Dam Outflow, R Street Bridge, South Prairie, Fairfax, Orting, Puyallup, National, McKenna, Rainier, Packwood, Randle, Mayfield Dam...Moderate flooding is forecast. For the Chehalis River Basin Region...including Bucoda, Centralia, Chehalis, Doty, Centralia, Grand Mound, Porter...Moderate flooding is forecast. ...FLOOD WARNING NOW IN EFFECT UNTIL EARLY THURSDAY MORNING... * WHAT...Moderate flooding is forecast. * WHERE...Nisqually River near National. * WHEN...Until early Thursday morning. * IMPACTS...At 10,000.0 cfs, the Nisqually River will flood along the upper reaches of the river from Mt Rainier National Park downstream to Alder Lake. Swift waters will flood roads...pasture lands...and farms. Erosion may damage the river banks. * ADDITIONAL DETAILS... - At 9:00 AM PST Tuesday the flow was 7,390.0 cfs. - Flood flow is 8,000.0 cfs. - Forecast...The river is expected to rise to a crest of 12,800 cfs late this afternoon. It will then fall below flood stage tomorrow afternoon. - http://www.weather.gov/safety/flood &&
info.instruction: Turn around, don`t drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood deaths occur in vehicles. Motorists should not attempt to drive around barricades or drive cars through flooded areas. Caution is urged when walking near riverbanks. Additional information is available at www.weather.gov. The next statement will be issued by this afternoon at 545 PM PST.
